    <!-- blog Section -->
    <section id="blog" class="blog_wrapper">
        <div class="container-fluid">
            <div class="row">
                <div>
                    <h3 class="blog-title">Why Many College Grads Can't Find Jobs...</h3>
                  <p class="blog-subtitle"><b>Published by Kyra Young, </b>04/25/2022 | 1:00pm</p>
                  <p class="blog-paragraph">"Obtaining employment after college is often difficult and the reasons for this are vast. Some individuals fail to do their part, other times the situation is out of their control. Some graduates accept the first job they find without realizing the potential impact it may have on their future". In this blog, I'll discuss why it's so <i><a class="first-link"  href="https://www.fairobserver.com/region/north_america/why-cant-college-graduates-find-jobs-43495/">hard to get a job</a></i> after college, list some reasons why and offer a list of tips to help. In addition, new graduates are often leaving college without the knowledge necessary to conduct an effective job search. Not knowing what jobs are a fit or what can be done with a specific major is clearly an obstacle. Unfortunately, this information is readily available as colleges can collect this data from alumni, but, in most cases, this information is not available to students.<br><br>It is my belief that every college should provide students with a professional development course regardless of their major. I am currently enrolled at NJIT as a junior, majoring in information systems. Last fall semester I had transferred from <a class="BCC-link" href="https://bergen.edu/"><b><i>Bergen Community College</i></b></a>. While back at that school, I do not recall my professors ever discussing the topic of networking, making connections, or just any advice on how to easily apply our skills gained from college to real life job opportunities. NJIT offers a manditory course for students taking a technology major. I took it last year and I learned how to properly write a resume, cover letter, practiced how to do a personal pitch, and learned the importance of creating Handshake and Linkedin accounts.<br><br> Students with mostly tech and medical degrees rank amongst the highest of individuals claiming to have difficulties landing an internship or full-time entry role. I recommend the following steps to recent or soon-to-be college graduates:</p>
                  <ol>
                    <p class="blog-lists">
                    <li>Create personal projects to show on resume</li>
                    <li>Research about jobs you are into</li>
                    <li>Create resume</li>
                    <li>Network(connect/reach out to recruiters)</li>
                    <li>Start applying for jobs</li>
                    </p>
               </div>
              </div>
      
      <style>
